roud, Gloucestershire, England":"Stroud, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gilbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), French, and German: from the personal name <i>Giselbert</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble youth’ (see   Giesel  ) + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This personal name enjoyed considerable popularity in England during the Middle Ages, partly as a result of the fame of Saint Gilbert of Sempringham (1085–1189), the founder of the only native English monastic order.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: The Devon family of Gilbert can be traced to Geoffrey Gilbert (died 1349), who represented Totnes in Parliament in 1326. His descendants included Sir Humphrey Gilbert (died 1583), who discovered Newfoundland. — Étienne Gilbert from Aulnay in Vienne, France, married Marguerite Thibault in Neuville, QC, in 1683. Louis Gilbert <i>dit</i> Comtois from Besançon in Doubs married Anne Jacques in Charlesbourg, QC, in 1722. Pierre Gilbert from Barbezieux-Saint-Hilaire in Charente, France, married Marie-Angélique Dufour in Petite-Rivière-Saint-François, QC, in 1756. Charles Dupuis <i>dit</i> Gilbert from Rosnay in Indre, France, married Marie-Jeanne Brunet in Sainte-Foy, QC, in 1741."],"variants":[{"name":"Gieseke","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ). Compare   Giesecke  ."]},{"name":"Giliberto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Constantino, Costantino, Emilio, Rosario, Santo, Sebastiano, Vittorio.","Italian: from an ancient Germanic personal name (see   Gilbert  )."]},{"name":"Gipp","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the personal name <i>Gipp</i>, a pet form of   Gilbert  . See also   Gibbs  . Alternatively, if pronounced with a soft <i>g</i>, it is a variant of <b>Jepp</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Jep(p)</i>, <i>Gep(pe)</i>, a pet form of   Jeffrey  .","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with the stem <i>geb</i> ‘gift’, as in <i>Gebhard</i> (see   Gebhardt  )."]},{"name":"Gilbertson","meanings":["English (northern): from the personal name   Gilbert   + <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Giesel","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Giesel</i>, a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble offspring’. In ancient and medieval ancient Germanic society, the younger children of kings and princes were sometimes sent to be brought up at the court of a neighboring ruler, as a pledge of peace between the two nations or clans. Thus, the male personal name <i>Gisil</i> and its feminine equivalent <i>Gisela</i> mean both ‘pledge’ and ‘noble offspring’."]},{"name":"Gilb","meanings":["German: from a short form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gibert","meanings":["French and German: from a shortened form of the personal name   Gilbert  . This name was also brought to England by Huguenot refugees in the 17th century.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Giese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Klaus, Erwin, Heiner, Heinz, Uwe, Aloysius, Armin, Dieter, Erhard, Ewald, Frieda.","German, Dutch, and Danish: from a short form of the personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  ), or any other ancient Germanic name with <i>gīsil</i> ‘hostage, pledge, noble offspring’ (see   Giesel  ) as the first element. Compare   Giesey  ."]},{"name":"Gibby","meanings":["English (Pembrokeshire): from a Middle English pet form of the personal name   Gilbert  ."]},{"name":"Gebbie","meanings":["Scottish (Ayrshire and Lanarkshire): from a pet form of the Norman personal name <i>Giselbert</i> (see   Gilbert  )."]}]},{"name":"Christina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Christina Gilbert was born in 1272, in Stroud, Gloucestershire, England. She married Ralph de Harding in 1285, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1287, in Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 15."},"et":{"1272–1287":"1272–1287","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1287–1305":"1287–1305","1305":"1305","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","1285":"1285","after 1285":"pärast 1285","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridge, Stroud, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Stroud, Gloucestershire, England":"Stroud, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1272–1287":"1272–1287","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1287–1305":"1287–1305","1305":"1305","Abt 1287":"noin 1287","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","1285":"1285","after 1285":"1285 jälkeen","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","Cambridge, Gloucestershire, England":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cambridge, Stroud, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridge, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Stroud, Gloucestershire, England":"Stroud, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"1272–1287":"1272–1287","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée","1287–1305":"